<p><a href="#sdfootnote22anc" name="sdfootnote22sym">22</a><sup></sup> The universalization of office work, symbolized herein by the IKEA office furniture, is supposed to highlight the anonymity of content moderators (who thus become everymen), as well as their slave-like exploitation by the capitalist corporate machine. Just as control of the Web is based on a catalog of specific approaches, so office furniture that we use every day constrains our movements, limiting our range of motion to what its designers were able to envision. That is also why the recordings featured in <em>Dark Content</em> compel the audience to transcend their well-worn and practiced ways of using such furniture. Cf. Artur Szarecki, <em>Kapitalizm somatyczny. Ciało i władza w kulturze korporacyjnej </em>(Warsaw: Wydawnictwa Drugie, 2017).</p>
